CT angiography of the chest

CT angiography is a test that uses a CT scan and a special dye. The dye is called contrast. It helps make clear pictures of the blood vessels in your chest and upper belly. CT means computed tomography.

Other names for this test include:
Computed tomography angiography of the chest, CTA lungs, CTA chest for pulmonary embolism, CTA chest for thoracic aortic aneurysm, CTA lung for blood clot, and CT pulmonary angiogram.

You will lie on a narrow table. The table slides into the middle of the CT scanner.

Inside the scanner, an x-ray beam moves around you.

A computer makes many pictures of the body. These pictures are called slices. They can be saved, seen on a screen, or printed. The slices can also be put together to make 3-D pictures of the chest.

You must lie very still. Moving can make the pictures blurry. You may be asked to hold your breath for a few seconds at a time.

Most scans take only a few minutes. New scanners can take pictures of the whole body, from head to toe, in less than 30 seconds.

Some CT exams need contrast dye before the test. Contrast helps some areas show up better on x-rays.

Contrast may be given through an IV in your hand or arm. If contrast is used, you may be asked not to eat or drink for 4 to 6 hours before the test.

Tell your health care provider if you have ever had a reaction to contrast dye. You may need medicine before the test so you can get the dye safely.

Before you get contrast, tell your provider if you take the diabetes medicine metformin, also called Glucophage. You may need special steps to stay safe.

Contrast can make kidney problems worse in people whose kidneys do not work well. Tell your provider if you have had kidney problems.

Too much weight can damage the scanner. If you weigh more than 300 pounds, or 135 kilograms, ask your provider about the weight limit before the test.

You will be asked to take off jewelry. You will wear a hospital gown during the test.

The x-rays from the CT scan do not hurt. Some people feel uncomfortable lying on the hard table.

If you get contrast through an IV, you may feel:
- A slight burning feeling
- A metal taste in your mouth
- Warmth or flushing in your body

This is normal. It usually goes away in a few seconds.

A chest CT angiogram may be done:
- If you have signs of blood clots in the lungs, such as chest pain, fast breathing, or shortness of breath
- After a chest injury or trauma
- Before lung or chest surgery
- To look for a place to put a catheter for hemodialysis
- If your face or upper arms are swollen and the cause is not known
- To look for a possible birth defect of the aorta or other blood vessels in the chest
- To look for a widened artery, called an aneurysm
- To look for a tear in an artery, called a dissection
- To check certain blood vessels around the heart

Results are normal if no problems are seen.

A chest CT may show many problems in the heart, lungs, or chest area. These may include:
- A possible blockage of the superior vena cava. This large vein carries blood from the upper half of the body to the heart.
- Blood clots in the lungs.
- Problems with blood vessels in the lungs or chest, such as aortic arch syndrome.
- Aortic aneurysm in the chest, also called a thoracic aortic aneurysm.
- Narrowing of part of the main artery that carries blood out of the heart, called the aorta.
- A tear in the wall of an artery, called a dissection.
- Swelling or irritation of blood vessel walls, called vasculitis.
- Problems with lung blood vessels. These may include narrowing of lung veins or abnormal connections between lung arteries and veins. These abnormal connections are called arteriovenous malformations.

Risks of CT scans include:
- Being exposed to radiation
- An allergic reaction to contrast dye
- Kidney damage from contrast dye

CT scans use more radiation than regular x-rays. Having many x-rays or CT scans over time may raise your risk for cancer. But the risk from one scan is small. You and your provider should compare this risk with the benefit of finding the right diagnosis.

Most modern scanners use methods that lower the amount of radiation.

Some people are allergic to contrast dye. Tell your provider if you have ever had an allergic reaction to injected contrast dye.

The most common contrast dye given through an IV contains iodine. If you have an iodine allergy, you may have nausea, vomiting, sneezing, itching, or hives if you get this type of contrast.

If you must get this contrast, your provider may give you antihistamines, such as Benadryl, or steroids before the test.

